        <body>       
                                

                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Dear Dr Morais&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>Many thanks for<lb/> your kindness in copying for me<lb/> Luzzato&#39;s artistic epicedion&#44;<lb/> but I had already botained the<lb/> same from my friend J. Herta&#44; a<lb/> few months before.  I desire<lb/> to make a collection of them<lb/> for the &#34;&#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44;&#34; to whose Editor&#44;<lb/> I showed these poems and who<lb/> begged me to prepare them for<lb/> his magazine.<lb/></p>
            <p>Do you know of any other<lb/> composition similarly striking<lb/> in any language&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>De Kosei erroneously ascribes<lb/> the authorship of the <hi rend="underline">second</hi> poem<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>to Leo. de Modena&#44; instead of to<lb/> Moses Bassola&#44; who edited<lb/> the &#91;Hebrew&#93; in Mantua 1578<lb/> perhaps you can say with cer&#45;<lb/>tainty whether he or I am right&#63;<lb/>  May I beg of you&#44; for the transla&#45;<lb/>tion of the following poem&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>&#91;Hebrew&#93; 1<lb/>
                &#91;Hebrew&#93; 2<lb/>
                &#91;Hebrew&#93; 3<lb/>
                &#91;Hebrew&#93; 4<lb/>
                &#91;Hebrew&#93; 5<lb/>
                &#91;Hebrew&#93; 6<lb/>
                &#91;Hebrew&#93; 7<lb/>
                &#91;Hebrew&#93; 8<lb/>
                1 Chi nasce&#44; muor&#44; Dime&#44; che pass&#39; acerbo&#33;<lb/>
                2 Colto vien l&#39;huom&#44; cosi ordin&#39; il Cielo&#44;<lb/>
                3 Mose mori&#44; Mose gia car de verbo&#44;<lb/>
                4 Santa sia ogn&#39;huom&#44; con puro zelo&#44;<lb/>
                5 Ch&#39;alla meta&#44; gia mai senza riserbo&#44;<lb/>
                6 Arriu&#39; huom&#44; ma vedran in cangiar pelo&#44;<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>7 Le fin habiam&#44; ch&#39;al Cielo vero<lb/> ameno<lb/>
                8 Va l&#39;huomo va&#44; se viva assai&#44; se<lb/> meno.<lb/></p>
            
            <p>I have however and the version of this<lb/> same poem with some minor variations<lb/> for instance in line 1 the <hi rend="underline">other</hi> copy<lb/> has&#58; &#91;Hebrew&#93; and in l. 1 of the Italian<lb/> version <hi rend="underline">Oi me</hi> &#40;in 2 words&#41;; l. 2 of<lb/> Hebrew&#58; &#91;Hebrew&#93; and &#91;Hebrew&#93;; Ital. l. 4&#58; <hi rend="underline">pur</hi>&#59;<lb/> l. 5 of Ital.&#58; <hi rend="underline">giammai</hi> &#40;in 1 word&#41;;<lb/> l. 6 my version begins with&#58; &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> inst. of &#91;Hebrew&#93; and the Italian strangely<lb/> enough is like the above&#58; <hi rend="underline">Arriv</hi>&#39; huom&#59;<lb/> l. 7 of Ital. has&#58; <hi rend="underline">Sefin</hi> &#40;in 1 word&#41; and<lb/> <hi rend="underline">habbiam</hi>&#59; l. 8 Hebrew has&#58; &#91;Hebrew&#93; and<lb/> ibid. Italian has&#58; <hi rend="underline">Va&#39; l&#39;huom</hi> and<lb/> vive&#45;&#45;I fear the orthography &#38; punctuation in<lb/> both <hi rend="underline">copies needs much</hi> <sic>amendation</sic>.<lb/></p>
            <p>Of course the variations are not<lb/> very important&#44; but I should much<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>like to know which is the better<lb/> version.  You will not be wrath<lb/> with me&#44; dear Dr&#44; if I ask of<lb/> you to go through the difficulty<lb/> and recopy for me a <hi rend="underline">purified</hi><lb/> version with an English transla<lb/>tion of the <hi rend="underline">Italian</hi>.<lb/></p>
            <p>Any reciprocal service on<lb/> my part will be most<lb/> cheerfully rendered.<lb/></p>
            <p>Very faithfully &#38; obediently<lb/> Yours&#44;<lb/> George A. Kohut<lb/></p>
            <p>Father begs to be remembered most<lb/> cordially to you &#38; your dear<lb/> son.  Kindly carry my respects to him<lb/></p>
            </body>
